			<div class="tab-pane fade" id="bios">
				<p><strong>Ruth Wiwchar</strong></p>
				<p>Ruth Wiwchar has enjoyed a varied career as a music educator in the fields of Elementary Music education and Choral Music. A graduate of Brandon University, Hamelin University (St. Paul, MN) and Memphis State University, Ruth has worked with students in kindergarten through grade twelve, and has been privileged to teach a variety of courses at the University of Manitoba for over thirty-five years. As well as working with Pembina Trails Voices, Ruth has enjoyed working with the children, youth and adults at Westworth United Church where she was the Director of Music for twenty-five years. She has also taught elementary music methods courses with the University of Manitoba and was instrumental in instituting the School of Music&rsquo;s summer Orff Certification Program.</p>
				<p>Currently, Ruth is the Artistic Director of the award winning Pembina Trails Voices, a school division initiated choral program of nine choirs serving the families in the Pembina Trails School Division which is located in the southwest quadrant of the City of Winnipeg. Ruth conducts the internationally known Cantemus, and is co-conductor of PTV Boys and PTV Singers.</p>
				<p>Ruth is the first recipient of the Morna-June Morrow Award for Excellence in Music Education in Manitoba. She was awarded the Winnipeg Branch of the Manitoba Registered Music Teachers&rsquo; Professional Award and was honoured to be named &lsquo;Most Outstanding Director&rsquo; at the Young Prague Festival in 2006. In 2010, Ruth was presented with the Carl Orff Canada Special certificate “in appreciation of her dedication and outstanding work In the field of choral music and the leadership she has given to Canadian music educators.” The Manitoba Foundation for the Arts honoured Ruth by presenting her with the Lee Cameron Arts in Education Award.</p>
				<p>Ruth has served on the National Board of Carl Orff Canada, is the Past President of the Manitoba Choral Association, was a member of the committee that produced the United Church hymnal, Voices United and is active on the United Church&rsquo;s Winnipeg Presbytery Worship Committee. Ruth and her husband Dan have two grown sons, Stephen (Lisa), and Michael (Mara), and are enjoying two recent additions to their family, Reese and Jackson.</p>
				<p><strong>Pembina Trails Voices</strong></p>
				<p>Pembina Trails Voices is one of the premier youth and children&rsquo;s choral ensembles in Canada. The choir&rsquo;s roots were firmly planted in the former Assiniboine South School Division when, in 1981, two ASSD trustees, Verna Van Roon and Myrtle Zimmerman, approached music educator Jan Bratland with a proposal to form a choir to entertain at the annual provincial trustees meetings in Brandon.</p>
				<p>The choir did a fabulous job of performing for the assembled throng. They had such a wonderful time together that they refused to disband! In short order, members of the choir appealed to the school board to fund the continuation of the choir, and the board agreed. With support from Dr. Patrick Krescy, Assistant Superintendent, the Assiniboine South School Division, and led by Jan Bratland, this choir became known as the Assiniboine South Youth Choir, comprised of choristers from grade five through nine. They rehearsed once a week, presented two concerts a year and toured in the spring.</p>
				<p>In 1986, Dr. Garry Froese began his tenure with the choir and, within five years, added a girl choir and boy choir component within the structure of twice-weekly rehearsals. Throughout the years, various other ensembles branched out from ASYC, giving the choristers a myriad of vocal and choral opportunities.</p>
				<p>In 2002, Ruth Wiwchar joined the Assiniboine South School Division and was appointed Artistic Director of the Youth Choir. That same year the Assiniboine South and the Fort Garry School Divisions amalgamated to become the Pembina Trails School Division. The youth choir followed suit, changing the name to Pembina Trails Voices.</p>
				<p>With amalgamation came the opportunity for the choir to expand, both in the number of ensembles and in the number of choristers. Today, PTV is comprised of choristers from K through grade twelve and functions in a series of ensembles, reflecting the various stages of vocal and musical development. The choir currently presents a total of five major concerts a year.</p>
				<p>Touring is an integral part of the program for middle and senior years choristers. Sharing choral music with audiences throughout Canada, the United States, the Caribbean and Europe has brought an incredible richness and a depth of cultural awareness to the choristers. Touring highlights over the years include performing in Newfoundland, Prague, Vienna, and at New York&rsquo;s Carnegie Hall.</p>
