			<div class="tab-pane fade" id="notes">
				<p><strong>Brundib&aacute;r (The Bumblebee)<br />Hans Kr&aacute;sa</strong></p>
				<p>Born in Prague of German descent, Kr&aacute;sa, like many other Jewish artists, perished in the Nazi Holocaust. His tragically brief career knew its share of success, and promised even more. In 1927, when he was 28, one of his teachers, the esteemed composer / conductor Alexander Zemlinsky, helped promote Kr&aacute;sa&rsquo;s conducting career by taking him along to Berlin as his assistant at the Kroll Opera. By that time, Kr&aacute;sa&rsquo;s Symphony for Small Orchestra had already won a favourable reception in Zurich, Boston and New York. He received conducting offers from Berlin, Paris, and Chicago, but since he was unwilling to accept a post in a foreign country, he returned to Prague. He threw himself into multiple activities, including composing his first opera, <em>Verlobung im Traum</em> (Betrothal in a Dream, 1933, from a story by the celebrated Russian author, Fyodor Dostoyevsky). It was produced in Prague under the esteemed conductor, George Szell.</p>
				<p>Because Kr&aacute;sa was Jewish and a vocal anti-fascist, in August 1942 he was sent to the Terezín (Theresienstadt) facility near Prague, a transitional location for people destined for the death camps. The Nazis tried to disguise it as a pleasant place to stay, prettifying it for a visit by a Red Cross representative in June 1944, for example.</p>
				<p>At first, the Terezín authorities merely tolerated artistic activity, but eventually they encouraged it. Kr&aacute;sa composed several works there, and served as music director of a group that administered the inmates&rsquo; &lsquo;leisure&rsquo; time. On 16 October 1944, he was sent on to the Auschwitz camp, where he was murdered in the gas chambers two days later.</p>
				<p>His music displays a heady mixture of many contemporary trends, from Zemlinsky&rsquo;s late Romanticism to the expressionism of Schoenberg, the neo-classical style of Stravinsky, and Debussy&rsquo;s French impressionism. It contained, to quote the New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians, &ldquo;subversive humour, grotesque gestures, formal confidence and melodic lyricism.&rdquo; He himself said, &ldquo;I am sufficiently daring, as a modern composer, to write melodic music. This reflects my whole attitude to music, whether it is called modern or anything else. My music is strictly founded on the concept of accessible melodic character.&rdquo;</p>
				<p>Naturally for a composer who lived just 44 years, his catalogue is small. It includes chamber works, an Overture for small orchestra, and songs. For decades, his music, like that of other composers who fell victim to the Nazis, appeared to have died with him. In the mid-1980s, it began to resurface, leading to its first widespread appreciation.</p>
				<p>In 1934, Kr&aacute;sa composed incidental music for author Adolf Hoffmeister&rsquo;s play, Youth in Play. Four years later, when the Czech Ministry of Education and Culture sponsored a competition for a children&rsquo;s opera, Kr&aacute;sa and Hoffmeister continued their collaboration with <em>Brundib&aacute;r</em>. Not long after it had been completed, the Nazis invaded the country. Jewish art was forbidden from public performance, so the occupants of Prague&rsquo;s Jewish ghetto staged private performances in their homes and institutions. In 1942, <em>Brundib&aacute;r</em> was performed by the residents of one such place, the Prague Jewish Boys&rsquo; Orphanage. After three performances, the entire population of the orphanage, children and staff alike, was shipped to the camps.</p>
				<p>By that time, Kr&aacute;sa had already been sent to Terezín. The residents of the orphanage ended up there, too. One of the orphanage&rsquo;s staff members had hidden a piano / vocal score of <em>Brundib&aacute;r</em> in his luggage. He gave it to Kr&aacute;sa, who reconstructed the accompaniment for the instrumental forces that were available, a chamber orchestra of thirteen.</p>
				<p><em>Brundib&aacute;r</em> received no fewer than 55 performances in the camp, beginning on 23 September 1943. The Nazis recognized the usefulness of this situation as propaganda, to show how &lsquo;well&rsquo; they were treating the inmates. The outside world heard only about the delightful performances by the children of the camp, excerpts from one of which were released on film. The world was unaware that the cast had to be replenished constantly, as virtually all the children who performed in the opera were exterminated shortly after they did so.</p>
				<p><em>Brundib&aacute;r</em> was published in 1992, and has received numerous performances in many lands. On one level, the engaging music and story provide pleasant family entertainment. On another, echoes of the heart-piercing circumstances under which it was first performed, and its stirring messages of hope, cooperation, and the defiance of evil (embodied in <em>Brundib&aacute;r</em>, the Hitler-like organ grinder), give it much different and deeper resonance. This MCO performance uses an English-language text by the noted British opera director, John Abulafia. His production of <em>Brundib&aacute;r</em> for the Mecklenburg Opera Company, conducted by Anne Manson, was broadcast by the BBC in 1993.</p>
				<p>Scene 1 : Two children, Aninka and Pep&iacute;&#269;ek, have a sick mother, who needs milk to get better. They have no money to buy it from the milkman, so they decide to imitate the wicked, bullying organ-grinder, Brundib&aacute;r, and raise money by singing on a street corner. Brundib&aacute;r and a policeman chase them away. The children spend the night on a bench. A dog, a cat, and a sparrow offer to help them.</p>
				<p>Scene 2 : In the morning, the children and their friends, animal and human alike, drown out Brundib&aacute;r&rsquo;s organ playing and together sing a beautiful lullaby for Aninka and Pepiček&rsquo;s mother. Their performance earns them generous donations from passersby. Brundib&aacute;r steals their money, but the crowd of children chase him down and get it back. To conclude the opera, all the children sing a stirring song about friends banding together to gain victory over tyranny.</p>
				<p><strong>L&rsquo;Histoire du soldat (The Soldier&rsquo;s Tale)<br />Igor Stravinsky</strong></p>
				<p>Stravinsky shot to fame through his brilliant collaborations with the legendary Russian impresario, Sergei Diaghilev, and his dance company, Les Ballets russes: <em>The Firebird</em> (1910), <em>Petrushka</em> (1911) and <em>The Rite of Spring</em> (1913). The First World War temporarily put a halt to the partnership. The Bolshevik Revolution of 1917, through which the imperial Russia where Stravinsky had grown up was dismantled, also made a profound impact upon him, in terms both spiritual and practical.</p>
				<p>Settling in Switzerland, he solidified and expanded the creative relationship with an author, Charles-Ferdinand Ramuz, that had begun in 1915. The tempestuous events of recent history had virtually wiped out Stravinsky&rsquo;s income from his music and his family estates. To make ends meet, he and Ramuz cast about for a joint project that would be inexpensive to produce and could be toured profitably throughout Switzerland. A new Stravinsky style, Neoclassicism, was born of those practicalities. <em>The Soldier&rsquo;s Tale</em>, the fascinating hybrid work that was so different from virtually everything he had composed previously, showed where he was headed stylistically (and where he would remain for the most part, until the 1950s).</p>
				<p>Stravinsky found a subject for them to work with in an anthology of Russian folk tales that he came across in the vast library of his father, Fyodor, the principal operatic bass of the Mariinsky Theatre in St. Petersburg. The story about a hapless Soldier who strikes a Faust-like, eventually tragic deal with the Devil, was set during the nineteenth-century reign of Tsar Nicholas I. In Ramuz and Stravinsky&rsquo;s version, they minimized any references to a specific time and place, in order to make their version of the allegorical fable more universal.</p>
				<p>They decided to present it as a kind of staged narration with music and a bit of choreography. Something &ldquo;to be read, played and danced,&rdquo; was how they described it. The performing company would include a handful of actors and dancers, accompanied by an ensemble of clarinet, bassoon, cornet, trombone, violin, double bass, and percussion. The cast has sometimes been narrowed to a single actor, taking the parts of narrator, Soldier and Devil. Such will be the case at this performance.</p>
				<p>Producing The Soldier&rsquo;s Tale proved more complicated than Stravinsky &amp; Co. had expected. Securing sufficiently skilled performers, as well as adequate rehearsal time and funding, were only the largest of many obstacles. Relations among the creators proved fractious at times, and everything about the project was in a constant state of flux. It was rescued financially by Werner Reinhart, a generous Swiss patron, who underwrote all expenses.</p>
				<p>The premiere took place in Lausanne on 28 September 1918, under Ernest Ansermet&rsquo;s baton. Stravinsky recalled that the portable stage was the size of two armchairs. The show won great success. A tour had been set up, but the Spanish influenza pandemic that had already devastated the war-weakened citizens of other countries swept into Switzerland, infected the contracted performers, and forced the tour&rsquo;s cancellation. In addition, the conclusion of World War One a short time later made the concept of touring theatre unnecessary.</p>
				<p>The following year, Stravinsky re-established his relationship with Diaghilev. There was no possibility of the Ballets russes staging <em>The Soldier&rsquo;s Tale</em>, as the temperamental impresario held little interest in a project into which he had had no input. It was only after several years and several unsuccessful productions that this unique, multi-discipline presentation found its way to popularity. Its greatest currency has been through the instrumental concert suite that Stravinsky drew from it in 1920, but it makes its full impact only when presented as it was conceived.</p>
				<p>Stravinsky&rsquo;s tart, witty and rhythmically intricate score displayed several influences: Russian folk song, gypsy fiddlers (reflecting the plot, the violin often takes the musical spotlight), klezmer groups, the popular music of Spain (The Royal March is an example of the pasodoble), and his recent exposure to jazz (the ensemble sounds like a Dixieland band at times). &ldquo;My knowledge of jazz was derived exclusively from copies of sheet music,&rdquo; he admitted, &ldquo;and as I had never actually heard any of the music performed, I borrowed its rhythmic style not as played, but as written. I could imagine jazz sound, however, or so I liked to think. Jazz meant, in any case, a wholly new sound in my music, and <em>L&rsquo;Histoire du soldat</em> marks my final break with the Russian orchestral school in which I had been fostered.&rdquo; Among the music&rsquo;s other ingredients are parodies of military marches and popular music forms such as the tango, waltz and ragtime, and even two Lutheran chorales, including <em>Ein&rsquo; feste Burg ist under Gott</em>(A Mighty Fortress Is Our God).</p>
